The Heysel stadium disaster was one of the blackest days in English football history, but it also prepared the ground for the sportâ€™s spectacular rebirth in its ancestral home. John Williams, an expert on football fan behaviour from the University of Leicester, describes it as â€œa moment of deep national shameâ€. At Thatcherâ€™s behest, the Football Association suspended English clubs from European competition for a year. European governing body UEFA went further still, announcing a five-year ban on English clubs and an indefinite suspension for Liverpool that would last until 1991. An inquiry into what had happened at Bradford and Heysel â€“ as well as a riot at Birmingham Cityâ€™s St Andrews stadium in which a 15-year-old boy died â€“ led by leading judge Oliver Popplewell resulted in new, wide-ranging public order powers for police. Recorded incidents of hooliganism sloped off, while attendances in the English Football League the following season slumped to a post-war low of 16.5 million. But the lessons of Heysel were only partially learnt and four years later, on April 15, 1989, tragedy befell English football again at Sheffield Wednesdayâ€™s Hillsborough stadium. Anxieties about violence had spawned a culture of poor crowd management and over-aggressive policing, which led to 96 Liverpool supporters being horrifically crushed to death after they were herded into over-crowded pens prior to an FA Cup semi-final against Nottingham Forest. - Gentrification - Another report by another judge, this time Peter Taylor, found serious failings in the policeâ€™s handling of the tragedy and ushered in the all-seater stadiums with which the English game is now synonymous around the world. â€œHeysel and Hillsborough sparked a wider understanding in this country that the game was culturally important, but run through with fan-behaviour problems, lacked an effective voice for the non-hooligan customer, was being ineptly managed and was poorly served by the police and government,â€ Williams told AFP. â€œStadia in England were quickly modernised after Hillsborough, the game was opened up to new supporters and fan behaviour improved and was more effectively managed.â€ Closed-circuit television, the segregation of rival fans, a ban on alcohol and the use of stadium banning orders, allied to a process of gentrification caused in part by spiralling ticket prices following the advent of the Premier League in 1992, have largely forced hooligans out of English stadiums. There are isolated incidents â€“ such as when Millwall fans shockingly fought between themselves inside Wembley during an FA Cup semi-final in 2013 â€“ but the pitched battles of the 1970s and 1980s have faded into memory. Through these past few days, Iâ€™ve learned that I am not just that Chinese girl, nor am I that American girl. No one can be just one of anything. As we go through life living each day, we lose sight of who we really are when we compare ourselves to others so judgingly. We forget and oftentimes feel ashamed and stigmatized. (AP) â€” A system that replaces verbal communication between pilots and air traffic controllers with computerized messages was unveiled Thursday by federal aviation officials, who said the system will reduce delays during weather events and cut down on errors that occur during routine voice transmissions. The Federal Aviation Administration demonstrated the Data Communications system, called Data Comm, at New Jerseyâ€™s Newark Liberty International Airport. The system has been used on a trial basis since 2013 at the Newark and Memphis, Tennessee, airports. The system is used to communicate alternate routes for planes awaiting takeoff that are heading toward bad weather. Currently, the information is given by voice and can take several minutes as the pilot copies it down and reads it back to the controller, then enters it into the planeâ€™s computer system. Using Data Comm, the controller transmits the information with a few clicks of a mouse. The information also is sent simultaneously to the airlineâ€™s dispatcher, whom a pilot often has to consult before taking an alternate route that will expend more fuel. FAA Administrator Michael Huerta compared the old system to getting directions over the phone from a friend, copying them down and checking them to make sure theyâ€™re correct. â€œWith Data Communications, you donâ€™t have to call a friend for directions,â€ he said. â€œHis address is pre-programmed into your carâ€™s GPS system and all you have to do is press â€˜go.â€™â€ Data Comm is one facet of the FAAâ€™s Next Generation Air Transportation System, or NextGen, a long-term effort to transition from an air traffic control system based on World War II-era radar technology to one based on satellite technology. NextGen will allow planes to safely fly closer together using GPS navigation, increasing the number of aircraft that can land and take off at airports and allow planes to save time and fuel by flying more direct routes. The FAA hopes to have Data Comm implemented at 56 airports by the end of next year, said Gregg Anderson, the FAAâ€™s air traffic operations leader for the Data Comm project. Officials said the new system also can reduce errors that are inherent in back-and-forth verbal communications, particularly when using the verbiage employed in the industry â€” in a demonstration Thursday, one of the routes given to a pilot with the acronym TOUGH became â€œTango-Oscar-Uniform-Gulf-Hotel.â€ â€œThis is transformational,â€ said Ray Adams, head of the air traffic controllers union at Newark. â€œThis will save so much time.â€ Paul Cassel, senior vice president of flight operations for FedEx, said he has seen delays reduced by several minutes since the company began using the system at its hub in Memphis. United Airlines, which operates about 380 flights per day through Newark, hopes to have a little more than half its fleet equipped to use Data Comm in the next three years, said Jim Compton, Unitedâ€™s chief revenue officer. Roughly 800 planes are using Data Comm, Anderson said. The agency estimates that the benefits of the new system will be felt on a nationwide scale when that number reaches 1,900, or about 20 percent of the planes eligible to use it.

Eurynome - A Story of Creation. by Christine Lavadas Long, long in the past, far, far in the future, At that point, before the beginning, after the end, Where time and space do not exist, Where all colors and forms are lost in the blackness of void, There was a heavy vast silence, A profound eternal motionlessness, And nothingness and everything were the same. And then Eurynome, Gaia, Goddess of a thousand names, Mother of all, Sighed. And the sound of her breath echoed pleasingly in her ears. As if it were a foreseeing And yet as if it were remembrance, She heard summer breezes ruffling tall green grasses, And winter hurricanes howling through deep valleys, And the pounding of the sea, And the calling voices of all creation. And so Eurynome, Gaia, Goddess of a thousand names, Mother of all, Pursed her lips and whistled for the wind. Then slowly, smoothly, with perfect sensuality She rose up from the timeless bed of her infinite rest And caught up the wind In her cupped hands, In her streaming hair, In the billows of her skirts, And in the warm secret places of her body, And she danced. She danced delicately, she danced frenziedly, She danced in staccato rhythm and liquid movement, She danced with pure precision and orgiastic abandon, She danced gloriously, She danced holding the wind in her close embrace, She danced the love and the joy of creation. She danced and she danced. Speed Drill of the Day: Build Agility and Body Control with the T-Drill. The ability to stop and change directions quickly is critical to athletic success. The T-Drill is a simple cone drill that hones your ability to generate speed over a short distance and change directions effectively. The T-Drill forces you to sprint forward, backwards and side-to-side, all while constantly changing directions. It not only works on your speed and agility, but also your balance and body control. You can tweak the distance of the T-Drill to make it either more of a short agility drill or more of a longer, top-speed drill. How to Perform the T-Drill Arrange four cones into a T shape. The distance between the cones is up to you, but placing them somewhere between 5 and 8 yards apart is a good place to start. Begin at the cone at the bottom of the T. Sprint forward to the cone at the top center of the T. Breakdown and backpedal to the bottom cone. Breakdown and sprint back to the top center cone. Cutting either right or left, sprint to the cone in that direction (if youâ€™d like, you can have a partner point a direction to test your reactions). Breakdown and cut around that cone to switch directions and sprint to the farthest cone. Breakdown and cut around that cone to switch directions and sprint to the top middle cone. Make a crisp cut and sprint back through the bottom cone to finish the drill. Sets/Reps: 6-8 total reps, alternating the direction you run first This article originally appeared on STACK.com: Speed Drill of the Day: Build Agility and Body Control with the T-Drill

Navigating the Chinese music market can be a minefield for those that donâ€™t have the experience or connections in place and this piece sums it up as well as bringing some solid insight from someone directly on the ground in the PRC. To break it down there are a few components that we noted from the article that we wanted to share with our readers. 1. Distributing Music in Chinaï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ While a huge potential market in terms of numbers, the actual number of outlets to release music are mostly limited to the major web giants and telcos, something we have outlined in an earlier post at Rightsify. This has both pros and cons, while these companies do have the capital, resources, and user-base to get your music out there, the Western model and distribution infrastructure just isnâ€™t there, yet. As noted in the report Even after a deal has been struck and with the distributor/ label ready to deliver content directly to these services, many of these services continue to maintain their content farms as their main source of audio files and metadata. Most Chinese music services are unable to process XML or DDEX formats for ingestion, making it harder for international distributors to tap into these music services directly This is more of a case of the market needing to adopt to international standards and as these services continue to license more foreign content they will most likely become more integrated with international distributors.ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ 2. Accessing Music As withï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½most countries in the Asia-Pacific region, mobile is the name of the game and when it comes to accessing music, itâ€™s no different.ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ Major state-owned telcos such as China Mobile, China Telecom and China Unicom all have their own streaming services which are likely to be bundled into devices and the major web giants tend to use music as part of their broader network of products and services, whether it be mobile messaging, video or even hardware.ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ 3. Music Rights In terms of music rights in China, the copyright system is still in itâ€™s early stages and from what we gather the recording side is much more established than publishing. It is also important to note that some of the major publishers and other sizeable independent publishers have not assigned their digital rights to the collection society, Music Copyright Society of China (MCSC) and instead have engaged independent distributors to this task. Whilst the MCSC is already covering a lot of ground, the content of many other publishers needs to be policed, which they assign to individual distributors in China to negotiate and deal directly with the music services to license accordingly From a Western standpoint, the idea of assigning your collection rights to an independent third-party instead of an ASCAP, PRS or GEMA type organization sounds bizarre and maybe even radical but in the Chinese market it seems that this might be delivering better results and ultimately more revenue for rights holders. 4. Royalties and Reporting Expectedly, the royalty and reporting infrastructure still has a way to go before reaching international standards. Royalty reporting, or the lack of it, is one of the biggest areas holding back the long-term development of a healthier music industry ecosystem in China. Currently, Chinaâ€™s music services do not provide royalty reports or have systems that properly track music consumption by users. Over time the reporting factor is likely to evolve and adopt as the platforms and services that are acquiring music will become more dependent on music as an exclusivity tool that helps drive traffic and sales to other apps or services.ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ The analytics and data from music consumption is also lacking quite badly. Elizabeth Chitty | St. Catharines, Ontario Snow gathering below Rodman Hall Art Centre, on the banks of the Twelve Mile Creek. On February 20, I headed off with my dog, Rupert, to gather snow before the big melt that was predicted to start later that day. (This proved to be overstated.) I gathered snow in a used Mason jar from which I had previously eaten delicious pears preserved by DeVries Farm and sold at the St. Catharines Farmersâ€™ Market. Given that Vernal Pool is about place, the jar was an important choice for me as I have been a Serious Locavore for many years. Weir 5 is at the foot of the bank behind Rodman Hall and the Walker Botanical Garden. Ontario Power Generation (OPG) owns the creek bed and controls water flow in that area of the Twelve. I photographed my mason jar of snow below two of the OPG signs, warning the public of dangerous water. As a gathering practice, Vernal Pool also resonated for me with a project I did in the Walker Botanical Garden at Rodman Hall in 2002 when I placed 46 stainless steel bowls throughout the garden and documented their contents over a year in 433 photos. elizabethchitty.ca Read Elizabethâ€™s full blog post here. In listing the animals that should not be eaten, God forbids the consumption of scavengers and carrion eaters, which devour other animals for their food. Animals such as pigs, bears, vultures and raptors can eat (and thrive) on decaying flesh. Predatory animals such as wolves, lions, leopards and cheetahs most often prey on the weakest (and at times the diseased) in animal herds. When it comes to sea creatures, bottom dwellers such as lobsters and crabs scavenge for dead animals on the sea floor. Shellfish such as oysters, clams and mussels similarly consume decaying organic matter that sinks to the sea floor, including sewage. A common denominator of many of the animals God designates as unclean is that they routinely eat flesh that would sicken or kill human beings. When we eat such animals we partake of a food chain that includes things harmful to people. As nutritionist David Meinz observes: â€œCould it be that God, in His wisdom, created certain creatures whose sole purpose is to clean up after the others? Their entire â€˜callingâ€™ may be to act exclusively as the sanitation workers of our ecology. I canâ€™t say the same about the forbidden seafoods though. I still could, though Iâ€™d be blatantly going against God. So I wonâ€™tâ€¦.maybe. No I wonâ€™t. I donâ€™t want to sabotage my progress. I donâ€™t want to risk His wrath either. How to Time Training Peaks to Be Your Best When It Matters Most. All your hard work should culminate when you peak for key competitions. Timing training peaks simply means adjusting your training in anticipation of performing at your highest level when it matters most. Training too hard before a competition can cause fatigue and suboptimal performance. Training too little can cause skills and fitness to deteriorate prematurely. During this phase, you make subtle changes to the training load that allow your body to take advantage of the cumulative effect of training and increase skill development while maintaining necessary fitness levels. In a typical 12-week season or training cycle, the peaking phase should start three to four weeks before the most important competitions. The shorter the season or training cycle, the shorter the peaking phase. A peaking phase can still include competitions. If your key competition is a state championship, your peaking phase will include the playoffs or sectionals. Training Peak Timing In the Weight Room To decease soreness and stiffness, phase out all non-compound movement lifts like Leg Presses and Curls. You shouldnâ€™t be doing these anyway. To sharpen coordination and balance, phase in bodyweight exercises. Check out the video player above for a demonstration. Increase the time between lifting sessions. If you are lifting three days per week, cut it to two. Instead of lifting Monday, Wednesday and Friday, lift Monday and Wednesday to take full advantage of this adaptation for weekend competitions. You can still train heavy with compound movements. Keep the intensity high. On the Track or Field Cut back both density and volume that culminates with 25- to 50-percent reductions. Phase in more intensity and purpose. Practices now are more about quality of reps than quantity. Phase in more restorative and mobility exercises to recover from the increased intensity and purpose. Well-spaced, short, intense practices are sufficient to maintain fitness and allow for additional recovery. Timing training peaks requires maintaining a delicate balance. If your peaking phase has been carefully planned, you should feel energized and full of anticipation. You will be ready to perform to the best of your ability. To Be Situated at the Head of the Avenue. 16 MAR 1882. Austin Daily Statesman. A NEW STATE HOUSE. Our Capitol for the Interim. At a meeting of the capitol board yesterday morning it was decided to erect a building for the use of the state until the completion of the new capitol. The building will be situated at the head of the avenue on the vacant lot opposite the county courthouse. The contract calls for a building not to exceed forty-five thousand ($45,000) dollars, and to be delivered to the state on or before the first day of January, 1883. The structure is to be of brick and stone, with a frontage on the avenue of 115 feet, and to extend back on Mesquite street 100 feet, and to embrace 13,700 square feet of floor; to be three stories high, with plain and substantial brick or stone cornice and aggregate height of not less than forty-five feet; partition walls to be of brick or stone, and all walls to be constructed with flues for stoves. The first floor to be of cement and the second and third floors to be of pine and deadened. It is to be hoped that the building will answer the purpose of construction, and notwithstanding the quick time in which it is to be finished that it will reflect credit on the capitol board, as also the contractor who submits the most favorable bid to the board.

preprotext: The death of Ser Barristan has really gotten me thinking, because whilst he was never the most major character, in the books he still has a significant role in the remaining plot. A role that will presumably have to be filled by someone else. MAJOR BOOK SPOILERS UNDER THE CUT. DO NOT READ ON UNLESS YOUâ€™VE READ THE BOOKS or you donâ€™t mind getting the end of Daenerysâ€™s plot this season spoiled Well assuming they donâ€™t change everything.ï¿½ï¿½Who knows with this lotâ€¦ So about halfway through book 5, Dany and co attend the reopening of the fighting pits - and as book readers know, the noise and the blood and the corpses and the fresh meat lead to another character returning!ï¿½ï¿½ Drogon. Who proceeds to shoot fire at his mummy, forcing her to climb on his back, fly the heck out of Meereen and completely vanish until literally the final chapter of the book when she turns up in the Dothraki Sea. No one in Slavers Bay knows if sheâ€™s alive or dead. But the point is, after Dany vanishes, it is Barristan who takes control of the city. He declares himself Hand of the Queen, he takes Danyâ€™s new husband Hizdahr captive, and he takes command when Yunkai and the Ironborn attack. And obviously, he will not be doing any of that in the show. Because heâ€™s dead. But who could take over? Daario? Yes, its possible. Could Jorah make it back? Well he is on his way, and his show-only greyscale infection could be a parallel for the bloody flux, or even a parallel with the cut greyscale-infected character Jon Connington rushing to secure the rule of his favourite cut-from-the-show-maybe-Targaryan. Missandei? Sheâ€™s the only one of Danyâ€™s advisors left practically, and it sure would be interesting to see her handling real power for the first time in her life. But thereâ€™s another character whose show fate I am wondering about. Tyrion. In the books, Tyrion does sort of make it to Meereen, but only after he, Jorah and Penny (who the show has cut) are captured by slavers and wind up in the Yunkaiâ€™i camp outside the walls. However, Tyrion and Jorah arenâ€™t at sea anymore, so the capture seems less likely. Also, it doesnt seem like Yunkai is actually going to attack Meereen in the show, the Sons of the Harpy are the only threat the city is facing - so Tyrion canâ€™t end up in their camp. And anyway, we have this on set photo that suggests he is actually going to get to meet and be accepted by Daenerys. In fact, this looks rather like it could be the day of the fighting pit incident. Suggesting Tyrion will be there at the exact moment someone needs to take command. With no capture by slavers, no Yunkaiâ€™i attack, no Victarion Greyjoy with his dragonbinding horn, and no bloody flux, Iâ€™m kind of lost as to what Tyrionâ€™s storyline is going to be once he makes it to Dany. But, if he replaces Barristan, using his established organisation and leadership skills to manage the city until she returns, then a lot of plot holes would start to fall into place. How exactly itâ€™d pan out is an unknown, from what information I have about this season anyway. I mean the situation in Meereen only really got worse after Barristan took control, though in fairness to him he was under attack by two outside forces, one internal organisation, and there was also a plague. But of those problems the only one Tyrion would face is the Sons of the Harpy crisis - and of course we still donâ€™t know exactly what will happen with Dany, as when the books leave off she is ill, stranded in the middle of nowhere, and has been found by one of her old Dothraki enemies. We donâ€™t know if she will ever make it back to Meereen. But I wouldnâ€™t be surprised if Tyrion gets a lot of power and control in the Slavers Bay plot. Whatever Barristanâ€™s role would have been - I suspect it is going to end up falling to him.

The Representation of Gender in Ohio Universityâ€™s the Green Goat PART 3 of 3 By Kaleb Martin The third installment of â€œRepresentations of Gender in the Green Goatâ€ examines types of men which commonly appear in the humor magazine. Although a range of behaviors and stereotypes for men can be found within the Green Green, two which are most apparent are the Man as Amorous Opportunist and The Gentleman. Succinctly, the Gentleman tends to respect his partnerâ€™s boundaries, while the Amorous Opportunist is more concerned with fulfilling his own desires. They are portrayed as humorous characters for different reasons: the Amourous Opportunist is comical due to his persistent and shameless pursuit of female attention, while the Gentleman entertains readers by observing traditions and etiquette seen as â€œstuffyâ€ or outdated. Separate analyses of the two can be found below. 3. Â  Man as Amorous Opportunist (Figures 8 and 9) Within the pages of the Goat, comics and short stories often depict the male college students as the Amorous Opportunist, who seeks out any occasion to attempt to seduce women. He can be suggestive and sly or forward and shameless. Since the object of his affection is usually more cautious than he is, her boundaries predict the extent of the pairâ€™s activities. Â In figure 8, the male character leans towards his love interest, seeming to pull her closer to his body. She faces away from him, expressing her reticence. He verbally suggests his desirous intentions for her. Figure 9 provides another example of the innuendo and ulterior intentions of the Amorous Opportunist.Â  4. Â  The Gentleman (Figures 10 and 11) Seemingly the opposite of the Amorous Opportunist, the Gentleman finds himself in similar territory as the former, while maintaining his manners and romantic sensibilities. As in figure 10, he asks permission before making advances, often to the point of making his partner impatient. His sincerity matches his partnerâ€™s or contrasts with their flippancy. Figure 11 illustrates the whimsical prose of the gentleman contrasted with the indifference of his partner. The Gentleman can be understood to represent the tradition, etiquette, romantic norms of the nineteenth century. Read Part 1 and Part 2 of the 3 part series

In 1996, one year after Maxinquaye, his most acclaimed work to this day, and before following Pre-Millennium Tension, Tricky used a different pseudonym and released Nearly God as an eponymous album. So it lies aside from his main discography, and therefore seems to be overlooked. But in terms of quality itâ€™s an exceptional and cohesive record which is at least as good as two aforementioned ones. Poems (featuring vocals of Tricky, Terry Hall and Martina Topley-Bird) is a leading song here, reminding what this music is about since others feel the same way. No track is purely instrumental and you can hear a lot of another guests along the album (even Bjï¿½ï¿½rk). However for me its main strength doesnâ€™t lie in vocals or lyrics, but in a unique mood and Nearly God achieves that more than any other Trickyâ€™s record I know. Four covers included â€“ opening Tattoo, Black Coffee, Judas and Childrenâ€™s Story â€“ are proving Trickyâ€™s ability to pick another artistsâ€™ songs and interpret them to work for his own cause. They continue seamlessly in already set up atmosphere almost making you believe they were written specifically for this album (Black Coffee is pretty old one by the way). It would be great to see Tricky with Topley-Bird doing together a regular tour nowadays, but I am afraid it wonâ€™t happen anytime soon. And I donâ€™t mean that only because of laterâ€™s absence, but because Adrian Thaws apparently doesnâ€™t give a shit. I donâ€™t blame him for such attitude, I just donâ€™t get it why he performs live if he feels like that. I was already warned about this, yet still went and saw him at Prague a few years ago and it wasnâ€™t anything else but disappointment. You could tell he was so uninvolved there just by taking a brief look at him, provided you actually saw him at all. Then he had another gig here recently and I rather passed an opportunity this time. Turned out to be a good decision because from what I read, it was basically the same screw over like before. Itâ€™s a shame and although I donâ€™t listen to Tricky for so long as, say, associated Massive Attack, he eventually became my most favourite artist of whole trip-hop genre. And everytime I hear one of his older records, it reasserts me he still is.

On No-Churn Ice Cream. After seeing a bunch of stuff about no-churn ice cream come up in various places recently, I decided to take a stab at it myself and see what kind of edible mess I could make. I acquired the ingredients. I planned out what I was going to do. This is my story. [Insert â€œLaw & Orderâ€ Chime Here] Like I said, I had come across a number of different No-Churn recipes in a short period of time so I kindaâ€™ winged it. I pulled from a few but the one I had open while I worked was this Instructables right here -> [Link] The recipe for this stuff is dirt simple - One Pint Heavy Cream, One Can (either 14oz or 12oz) Condensed Milk. From that, you have a blank canvas to mess up as much as you want. The vegan version is just as simple with a can of coconut cream (aka - the solids from coconut milk) and some non-dairy milk like almond milk and the like. Thatâ€™s next on my list to try but back to This batch for now. = ) I had a pack of Land â€˜o Lakes White Hot Chocolate kickinâ€™ around from the winter that I wanted to toss in something - be it a baked good or maybe some coffee - and this seemed like the perfect item. I also got some Andes Mints for some tasty texture (and â€˜cause I like having a reason to buy them besides â€œIâ€™m going to eat all of these before I get home.â€). I also picked up the ingredients for the ice cream base. Where I really deviated from the recipes I found was I made it a point to control the sugar content. This was two-fold: 1) I wanted a slightly less sweet base so I could mess around more with the flavors without killing myself and others with sweetness. 2) My uncleâ€™s a diabetic. My aunt more than likely is, too. Theyâ€™ll have access to this once Iâ€™m done so yeah! A good idea to control the sugar level just in case they dig it and blow through it. I got lucky in that I found a store brand condensed milk that ran 17g of sugar where the bigger brands - Eagle Borden, Carnation and Nestle - tended to run in the low to mid-20â€²s. Itâ€™s not much, mind you, but anywhere I can cut without affecting flavor too terribly I had to try. Another thing I looked into was subbing out condensed milk for coconut cream but I was afraid the slight coconut taste could mess with all that chocolate Iâ€™m dropping into this. The white hot chocolate I used is light already, with a flavor akin to a really good vanilla bean than traditional chocolate. Anything too heavy runs the risk of overpower it. I know this from forgetting I had loaded a coffee K-Cup in my coffee machine when I just wanted to use it to boil the water for the hot chocolate. It was a delicious mistake. = ) Anyhoo! Without further adoâ€¦ White Chocolate No-Churn Ice Cream with Mint Chocolate Chunks: - Ingredients One Pint Heavy Cream One 14oz Can Condensed Milk One 1.25 oz Packet Land Oâ€™ Lakes Classic Arctic White Cocoa mix One small package Andes Creme de Menthe candies - Tools Large Glass Mixing Bowl Mixer (Manual or Electric) Spatula Loaf Pan or Other Container (Optional) - Steps Place mixing bowl in freezer â€˜till chilled along with the Andes candy. Remove mixing bowl. Empty white hot chocolate and heavy cream into bowl and combine. Whip to soft peaks. Slowly fold in condensed milk and combine â€˜til uniform in color. Place in freezer for an hour. Use this time to crush Andes into small chucks. Fineness is up to you. Remove ice cream from freezer and fold in candy bits. Place in freezer for about four to six hours in container of choice. Scoop and enjoy. Some folks whipped theirs to stiff peaks. I went to soft at first â€˜cause I was using a manual mixer and my arms were pretty damn tired after 45mins. Why not use an electric hand mixer? â€˜Cause I started this at 11pm while doing laundry and the hand mixer is loud and kindaâ€™ terrible. Having been Years since I last had to fold in a product, my nice soft peaks fell flat and I decided to (Very Carefully) whip more air into it. This may or may not have lead to the end product being fairly thick. I also think the white hot chocolate mix I used helped in that as it was always a fairly thick. Another change Iâ€™d make is using more candy. The Andes were a bit harder to crack than expected but itâ€™s doable. I only used ten out of a pack of twelve and the scoops in that pic tell the tale. Next time, Iâ€™m going to go with the Andes baking chips - both for size, amount and I donâ€™t have to beat â€˜em up before I add them. All in all, a good first try. Going to have to make another attempt laterâ€¦ and put a little more practice into my folding technique. -.-

THATâ€™S WHAT DANTE HAS ALWAYS BEEN! I will agree with fans, Dante is very different from his previous incarnations, both physically and mentally. However youâ€™ll notice by doing some strict factual comparisons that they are alike in many of the key things that made the original Dante a hit! Both are gigantic smart-asses! Dante treated a giant Cerberus like a puppy! (DMC3), meanwhile Dante in DmC made every bad breakup joke in the book to the succubus. Both are trigger happy! Iâ€™ve seen many instances in which all the forms of Dante would rather just shoot their way out of any situation. Take for instance Jester in DMC3, Dante threatened to shoot him many times and also tried in many instances.ï¿½ï¿½ I could go on but for the sake of time I wonâ€™t. The point being is that Dante didnâ€™t change all that much. Just small differences that seemed really big at the time.ï¿½ï¿½ What about another fan favorite character?ï¿½ï¿½ Vergil, the other son of Sparda. Hell he stabbed Arkham cause he thought he got soft. Now here we find that the reboot got it wrong! The Vergil in the remake was dependent on his order, he was more focused on his political power-plays working than in his physical strength. And yet this is a very good representation of what Vergil could have been, before Devil May Cry 3, his debut.ï¿½ï¿½ Think of this, this game happened before Vergil went BSC, (Bat shit crazy) we know that because we witnessed his downfall in the DLC. So obviously this isnâ€™t the same Vergil but there are some very important events that show this Vergil turns into the DMC3 Vergil.ï¿½ï¿½ The most important fact is his treatment of Kat after she is captured. Vergil was all to willing to let her die, as far as he was concerned, she had outlived her usefulness.ï¿½ï¿½ Does that sound familiar? It should. Vergil did the exact same thing to Arkham in Devil May Cry 3, The second Arkham showed a little bit of humanity concerning his daughter, He exceeded his usefulness in Vergilâ€™s eyes.ï¿½ï¿½ While he may not be the power hungry man in DmC, Vergil is still ruthless in his goals.ï¿½ï¿½ Speaking of Kat, isnâ€™t it odd we never see her again after the game? An original character, or something else. If you would I would like to submit evidence that Kat is in fact, Maryâ€™s sister.ï¿½ï¿½ These are both official images from both games, obvious physical differences aside we never know too much about Kat, other than she has is a medium, she can go in between Limbo and the physical world. In essence she is a human with a deep connection with demons. All we know of her past is that she has constant nightmares and she is an orphan.ï¿½ï¿½ Lady on the other hand has a strong hatred of demons because of her Father who sacrificed her mother in a demonic ritual. She wants to kill all demons, and doesnâ€™t care who they are. In fact she tried to kill Dante, three times. Now my own GAME THEORY!! (Reference!)ï¿½ï¿½ Kat and Mary are both sisters, with Mary being the oldest. She seeâ€™s her father kill their mother and runs taking Kat with her, leaving her in the care of someone in the city. Kat runs even farther and Mary canâ€™t find her, and assumes sheâ€™s dead. Kat learns about strange things in her hometown and thinks Mary is dead. Now again this is just to show you that the characters arenâ€™t really that different.ï¿½ï¿½ Now are these two related. Maybe, maybe not.ï¿½ï¿½ But I do know this, they are the only characters in the entire series to have huge, ground-breaking roles in these games despite the face that they are both humans.ï¿½ï¿½ And now my closing argument: I know exactly why this reboot failed where others of itâ€™s ilk were successful. Iâ€™m not going to bother linking to all of the articles written about the fact that Esteemed Literary Author Kazuo Ishiguro wrote a book with fantastical elements. It was astounding how many people were still surprised that fantastical stories can be stylistically complex, that genres can blend. Anyway. THE BURIED GIANT is not a very innovative fantasy: a man and a woman go on a quest and meet up with some knights who want to defeat a dragon who lives high in a mountain. But it is a beautifully written book with a profound (and profoundly sad) meditation on love and companionship. Elderly couple Axl and Beatrice want to leave their safe community to visit their son, who they believe lives in a town just a few daysâ€™ walk away. Their confusion about the details stems not from their age but from aï¿½ï¿½â€œmist,â€ descended upon the country (medieval England), which makes people forget the past. They canâ€™t particularly remember their lives together, although they assume their days to be happy. As they travel they hear unsettling stories about boatmen who promise to ferry couples across to an island together only if they prove to have an unusually strong bond; Beatrice is afraid they have forgotten too many of their shared memories to make safe passage together. Sir Gawain (yes, the Arthurian one) makes an appearance, as do a boy bitten by a dragon, a â€œshe-dragon,â€ and some suspect sheep. Sir Gawain narrates a few sections that could have easily been cut, and the long digressions into the travels of the knight and the boy are disappointingly thin. Ishiguroâ€™s storytelling is unsettling, and his novels often haveï¿½ï¿½â€œtwistsâ€ that are revealed so slowly as to shock the dazed reader only paragraphs after the factâ€“ NEVER LET ME GO and REMAINS OF THE DAY being good examples. In THE BURIED GIANT, theï¿½ï¿½â€œtwistâ€ was clear to me early on, I think because the book so closely hews to basic fantasy tropes. The novel is worth reading for its heartbreakingly astute observations on the way memory can both bind and destroy a romantic relationship, but I think fantasy fans will be turned off by the ordinary plot and literary fans by the clunky use of fantasy. The interest based values of liberalism and the basic general good philosophy of utilitarian ethics that emerged through the course of the enlightenment has effectively changed the conception of human nature, disavowing its ends. The individual emerged as something apart from the society in which it lives, as a creature without itâ€™s being in history, that is to say without embodying an objective nature in relation to the cultural and social milieus in which we live. MacIntyre observes that this treatment has been used to render all moral philosophy of varying context and subject matter, flattening the lived narrative qualities into subjected volumes. Abstracting the individual from the self as a person who exists in relation to others, advances the myth that we live independently of one another (2012; 11), leaving the person bare and without a compass. Emotivism has taken the place of natural law. MacIntyre writes, â€œwhat emotivism asserts is in central part that there are and can be no valid rational justification for any claims that objective and impersonal moral standards exist and hence that there are no such standardsâ€ (2012; 19). Emotivism emerges from an indictment against the whole of moral philosophy, claiming â€œthat every attempt, whether past or present to provide a rational justification for an objective morality has in fact failedâ€ (MacIntyre 2012; 19). The whole project of individuation was turned against those traditional modes of existence that bound persons and communities together. Religion, virtues and philosophy lost their central place in the order of society; reason, the nation-state and the market filled the overturned position. MacIntyreâ€™s central claim is that moral issues can never be settled in our modern liberal society and instead they multiply. We have been able to frame laws, declaring rights, which are by design and practice ceaselessly open to interpretation, yet we experience drift in relation to truth. Culturally we have become stuck in our debates over issues like euthanasia, social justice, and the use of military force. We can hardly agree on what is we personally owe to one another, and MacIntyre argues that this is because we have lost or given up the moral language, the instrument that guides our reasoning towards keeping with the common good. Now â€œwe possess no rational way of weighing the claims of one as against the otherâ€ (MacIntyre 2012; 8). Modernism in its renunciation of moral argument, normative power, and truth identifies itself as a process of endless toil, characterized by a sense that moral injunctions possess no grounds for legitimacy. The thinkers of the Enlightenment emerged from a background that had forsworn allegiances to classical philosophical and Christian moral practices. The academy beat the ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½lan vital out of the rug for being superstitious, unscientific, and having no material currency with velocity. Experimental: Frame and Final Piece. After the curation and selection of the images for my final piece, I set about contacting framers to get the deep frame made. I save money by not having a glass front to it, and I stuck the images down in place myself to avoid another cost. I managed to get the frame to cost ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½100, a reduction of half the originally quoted. Using maths and a ruler and 88 sticky pads i created a line of the Polaroids on the big mount board, making sure the line was equal at all points. The framer commended me on my accuracy! The pads had to be piled 4 high on each other to create enough depth so that the pictures would be suspended with a shadow behind them. I had to allow 2 inches around all sides, plus the frame width, as the backing would have to be mounted in a special way to retain the box frame depth. I then left the frame to be finished by the framer. The frame looks great finished, and has a very sturdy back so there is no danger of it breaking or twisting in the frame over time.
